      <hedline>
        <hl1>Does Religion Have a Public Role?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rabbi Bernhard H Rosenberg letter, commenting on August 28 article on Sen Joseph Lieberman's advocacy of greater role for religion in public life, says he is creating dangerous precedent that undermines priciple of separation of church and state</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lieberman Seeks Greater Role for Religion in Public Life'' (news article, Aug. 28):</p>
        <p>The presidential race is turning into a religious convention.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lieberman Seeks Greater Role for Religion in Public Life'' (news article, Aug. 28):</p>
        <p>The presidential race is turning into a religious convention.</p>
        <p>The wearing of one's religion on one's sleeve creates a dangerous precedent and undermines the principle of separation of church and state. One religion will be turned against another, with candidates exploiting their own personal religious convictions.</p>
        <p>While we would like to believe that we live in an age of newfound tolerance, the truth is that intolerance, anti-Semitism, bias and bigotry still exist in the United States.</p>
        <p>(Rabbi) BERNHARD H. ROSENBERG  Edison, N.J., Aug. 29, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
